.SS "Logger Handlers"

.PP
Two standard logger handlers are defined in the Kernel application. These are described in the Kernel User's Guide, and in the \fIlogger_std_h\fR and \fIlogger_disk_log_h\fR manual pages.

.SS "OS Signal Event Handler"

.PP
Asynchronous OS signals may be subscribed to via the Kernel applications event manager (see OTP Design Principles and \fIgen_event\fR) registered as \fIerl_signal_server\fR. A default signal handler is installed which handles the following signals:

sigusr1
.RS 2
The default handler will halt Erlang and produce a crashdump with slogan "Received SIGUSR1". This is equivalent to calling 
\fIerlang:halt("Received SIGUSR1")\fR.

.RE

sigquit
.RS 2
The default handler will halt Erlang immediately. This is equivalent to calling 
\fIerlang:halt()\fR.

.RE

sigterm
.RS 2
The default handler will terminate Erlang normally. This is equivalent to calling 
\fIinit:stop()\fR.

.RE

.PP
\fBEvents\fR

.PP
Any event handler added to \fIerl_signal_server\fR must handle the following events.

sighup
.RS 2
Hangup detected on controlling terminal or death of controlling process


.RE

sigquit
.RS 2
Quit from keyboard


.RE

sigabrt
.RS 2
Abort signal from abort


.RE

sigalrm
.RS 2
Timer signal from alarm


.RE

sigterm
.RS 2
Termination signal


.RE

sigusr1
.RS 2
User-defined signal 1


.RE

sigusr2
.RS 2
User-defined signal 2


.RE

sigchld
.RS 2
Child process stopped or terminated


.RE

sigstop
.RS 2
Stop process


.RE

sigtstp
.RS 2
Stop typed at terminal


.RE

sigcont
.RS 2
Continue after stop


.RE

sigwinch
.RS 2
Window size change


.RE

siginfo
.RS 2
Status request from keyboard. Note several operating systems (Linux in particular) do not support this signal. 
\fIos:set_signal/2\fR will thow a \fIbadarg\fR exception if support is missing.

.RE

.PP
Setting OS signals are described in \fIos:set_signal/2\fR.

.SS "Configuration"

.PP
The following configuration parameters are defined for the Kernel application. For more information about configuration parameters, see file \fIapp\fR.

connect_all = true | false
.RS 2
If enabled (
\fItrue\fR), which also is the default, \fIglobal\fR will actively connect to all nodes that becomes known to it. Note that you also want to enable \fIprevent_overlapping_partitions\fR in order for \fIglobal\fR to ensure that a fully connected network is maintained. \fIprevent_overlapping_partitions\fR will also prevent inconsistencies in \fIglobal\fR's name registration and locking.
.PP
The now deprecated command line argument \fI-connect_all <boolean>\fR has the same effect as the \fIconnect_all\fR configuration parameter. If this configuration parameter is defined, it will override the command line argument.


.RE

